"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657740","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-12-19","<p>The RAF maintains sufficient fuel stocks at Leuchars Station to refuel military aircraft required to use the diversionary runway.</p>",,"Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657740/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-19T16:11:08.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657740/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657740/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-12-13","Leuchars Station","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what provision has been made for the refuelling of aircraft required to use the diversionary runway at Leuchars.","false","Biography information for Lord Campbell of Pittenweem",,"Lord Campbell of Pittenweem","HL4059"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657741","HM Treasury","false","2016-12-19","<p>Receipts from fuel duty are published in the Hydrocarbon Oils statistical bulletin and the figures from the last ten financial years are shown below:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Receipts (£ bn)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2006/07</p></td><td><p>23.6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2007/08</p></td><td><p>24.9</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2008/09</p></td><td><p>24.6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009/10</p></td><td><p>26.2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010/11</p></td><td><p>27.3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>26.8</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>26.6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>26.9</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>27.2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>27.6</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>For VAT, the information requested is not available. HM Revenue and Customs does not collect data on VAT revenues from particular goods and services.</p>",,"Lord Young of Cookham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657741/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-19T14:52:43.13Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657741/answer","Biography information for Lord Young of Cookham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657741/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-12-13","Fuels: Taxation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how much was raised on fuel duty and VAT on fuel for each of the last 10 financial years.","false","Biography information for Lord Darling of Roulanish",,"Lord Darling of Roulanish","HL4060"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657742","Department for Transport","false","2016-12-21","<p>Officials meet regularly with franchisees, and at these meetings assistance for passengers at such times may be one of the discussion topics. Each operator is required to participate in the Passenger Assist system which allows passengers to book staff assistance when they require it, and we expect Southern to ensure that passengers receive that assistance when required at all times.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657742/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-21T14:52:54.803Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657742/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657742/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-12-13","Southern","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what discussions they have had with Southern Rail to ensure that there are adequate support services for the elderly and disabled, particularly at times of reduced service.","false","Biography information for Baroness Gould of Potternewton",,"Baroness Gould of Potternewton","HL4061"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657743","Department for Transport","false","2016-12-21","<p>Holders of day tickets are able to claim compensation through the Delay Repay scheme. On 11 December we introduced Delay Repay 15 which applies to passengers with day single and return tickets as well as to season ticket holders. All passengers are able to claim 25% of the cost of the single fare for delays between 15 and 29 minutes. The existing compensation thresholds will apply for delays from 30 minutes with passengers able to apply for compensation through the train operating company. Delay Repay from 30 minutes is already one of the most generous compensation schemes in Europe.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657743/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-21T14:53:40.35Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657743/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657743/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-12-13","Southern: Compensation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether Southern Rail has made, or is considering, any proposal to provide compensation for regular passengers who do not hold a season ticket.","false","Biography information for Baroness Gould of Potternewton",,"Baroness Gould of Potternewton","HL4062"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657744","Department for Education","false","2016-12-20","<p>We want schools to provide all young people with a curriculum that equips them for success in adult life.</p><p> </p><p>High quality PSHE teaching has an important role to play in this, helping young people understand the world around them, building resilience and helping them to make positive choices and stay safe. We have made it clear in the introduction to the national curriculum that all schools should make provision for PSHE, drawing on examples of good practice. Academies and free schools are encouraged to teach PSHE as part of a broad and balanced curriculum.</p><p> </p><p>Sex education is already compulsory in secondary maintained schools, and the Government is clear that all schools should make provision for high quality, age-appropriate sex and relationship education (SRE) which is a vital part of preparing young people for life in modern Britain.</p><p> </p><p>The Secretary of State agrees that we need to look again at the case for further action on PSHE and SRE provision, with particular consideration to improving quality and accessibility. We are actively considering what steps we could take, including whether to update the existing SRE guidance and will give a view soon.</p>",,"Viscount Younger of Leckie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657744/answer",,,,,"HL4064","2016-12-20T15:42:09.133Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657744/answer","Biography information for Viscount Younger of Leckie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657744/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-12-13","Personal, Social, Health and Economic Education","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what progress is being made to introduce personal, health and social education in all (1) state schools, (2) academies, and (3) free schools.","false","Biography information for Baroness Gould of Potternewton",,"Baroness Gould of Potternewton","HL4063"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657745","Department for Education","false","2016-12-20","<p>We want schools to provide all young people with a curriculum that equips them for success in adult life.</p><p> </p><p>High quality PSHE teaching has an important role to play in this, helping young people understand the world around them, building resilience and helping them to make positive choices and stay safe. We have made it clear in the introduction to the national curriculum that all schools should make provision for PSHE, drawing on examples of good practice. Academies and free schools are encouraged to teach PSHE as part of a broad and balanced curriculum.</p><p> </p><p>Sex education is already compulsory in secondary maintained schools, and the Government is clear that all schools should make provision for high quality, age-appropriate sex and relationship education (SRE) which is a vital part of preparing young people for life in modern Britain.</p><p> </p><p>The Secretary of State agrees that we need to look again at the case for further action on PSHE and SRE provision, with particular consideration to improving quality and accessibility. We are actively considering what steps we could take, including whether to update the existing SRE guidance and will give a view soon.</p>",,"Viscount Younger of Leckie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657745/answer",,,,,"HL4063","2016-12-20T15:42:09.18Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657745/answer","Biography information for Viscount Younger of Leckie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657745/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-12-13","Sex and Relationship Education","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have any plans to introduce compulsory sex and relationship education in schools; and if not, why not.","false","Biography information for Baroness Gould of Potternewton",,"Baroness Gould of Potternewton","HL4064"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657746","Department of Health","false","2016-12-20","<p>There is no requirement on local authorities to have cross-charging arrangements in place; this is a matter for local determination.</p><p> </p><p>No estimate has been made of the number of local authorities that do not have cross-charging arrangements. Public Health England recently conducted a survey into the commissioning arrangements for sexual and reproductive health and HIV, including assessment of cross-charging arrangements.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657746/answer",,,,,"HL4066","2016-12-20T15:22:10.503Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657746/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657746/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-13","Genito-urinary Medicine","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the effectiveness of local authority cross-charging arrangements for sexual health services.","false","Biography information for Baroness Gould of Potternewton",,"Baroness Gould of Potternewton","HL4065"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657747","Department of Health","false","2016-12-20","<p>There is no requirement on local authorities to have cross-charging arrangements in place; this is a matter for local determination.</p><p> </p><p>No estimate has been made of the number of local authorities that do not have cross-charging arrangements. Public Health England recently conducted a survey into the commissioning arrangements for sexual and reproductive health and HIV, including assessment of cross-charging arrangements.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657747/answer",,,,,"HL4065","2016-12-20T15:22:10.603Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657747/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657747/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-13","Genito-urinary Medicine","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their estimate of the number of local authorities that have not developed cross-charging arrangements for the provision of sexual health services, as recommended in the report <i>Sexual Health Services: Key Principles for Cross Charging</i>, published in August 2013.","false","Biography information for Baroness Gould of Potternewton",,"Baroness Gould of Potternewton","HL4066"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657748","Home Office","false","2017-01-09","<p>The immigration rules for study migration currently differentiate by types of institution. We will be shortly consulting on how we could differentiate further to support the sector.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657748/answer",,,,,,"2017-01-09T13:13:59.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657748/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657748/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-12-13","Universities: Standards","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Baroness Williams of Trafford on 12 December, whether they will now answer the question asked; how they define "best"; and which universities they claim to be "best".","false","Biography information for Lord Harris of Haringey",,"Lord Harris of Haringey","HL4067"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657749","Leader of the House of Lords","false","2016-12-20","<p>As Leader of the House I take very seriously the responsibility incumbent on all Ministers to provide full, timely and comprehensible answers to Questions for Written Answer. This is something I stress regularly to frontbench colleagues and which I will certainly reiterate in the light of the Noble Lord’s question. My office also engage regularly with private offices and Parliamentary teams when issues arise, both proactively and in response to concerns raised by individual members. It is for Ministers, though, to be directly accountable for the content of their answers, which is why I fully support the rule that Ministers must personally sign all answers to members of the House of Lords.</p>",,"Baroness Evans of Bowes Park","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657749/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-20T17:18:58.72Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657749/answer","Biography information for Baroness Evans of Bowes Park","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657749/answer",,,,,"92",,"Leader of the House of Lords","2016-12-13","Written Questions","2","House of Lords","To ask the Leader of the House what arrangements are in place to ensure that, in answering Questions for Written Answer, government departments are, as required by the Ministerial Code, "accurate and truthful" and as "open as possible" in the answers they provide to members of the House of Lords; whether she has put in place a system to provide quality assurance of the answers provided by government departments to members of the House of Lords; and if so, what..","false","Biography information for Lord Harris of Haringey",,"Lord Harris of Haringey","HL4068"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657750","Cabinet Office","false","2016-12-20","<p>Section 1 of the Ministerial Code states that Ministers have a duty to be as open as possible with Parliament and the public, refusing to provide information only when disclosure would not be in the public interest. This should be decided in accordance with the relevant statutes and the Freedom of Information Act 2000.</p>",,"Baroness Chisholm of Owlpen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657750/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-20T15:38:37.663Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657750/answer","Biography information for Baroness Chisholm of Owlpen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657750/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-12-13","Parliamentary Questions","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of the statement in the <i>Companion to the Standing Orders and Guide to Proceedings of the House of Lords</i> that "A parliamentary question is not a request for information under the Freedom of Information Act 2000", whether answers to parliamentary questions should contain more or less information than a request for information under the Freedom of Information Act 2000.","false","Biography information for Lord Harris of Haringey",,"Lord Harris of Haringey","HL4069"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657751","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-12-21","<p>In publishing her review of Integration and Opportunity, Dame Louise Casey expressed hope that her report will spark a national conversation about improving the integration of communities in Britain, including establishing a set of values around which people from all different backgrounds can unite.</p><p>My Right Honourable Friend, Sajid Javid, the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, has made clear he will carefully consider the findings of Dame Louise’s review, in consultation with his Government colleagues and faith and other community leaders and will bring forward proposals in the spring.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657751/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-21T13:37:53.16Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657751/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657751/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-12-13","Citizenship","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they plan to initiate a national dialogue for Britain to discuss common citizenship, with active participation by people of all traditions and origins.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL4070"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657752","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-12-22","<p>There was never any justification for paramilitary groups in Northern Ireland and there is none today. The UK Government is committed to working with the Northern Ireland Executive to end paramilitary activity through the measures agreed in the Fresh Start Agreement, and to supporting legitimate and accountable community organisations. This Government believes in the rule of law and does not support amnesties.</p>",,"Lord Dunlop","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657752/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-22T11:55:04.11Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657752/answer","Biography information for Lord Dunlop","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657752/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-12-13","Terrorism: Northern Ireland","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what plans they are considering for offering rehabilitation and amnesty to members of militant groups in Northern Ireland who are willing to renounce violence and to pursue their aims by exclusively political and democratic means.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL4071"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657753","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-12-20","<p>The UK Government has made clear that it intends to fully involve Gibraltar as we prepare for exit from the EU, to ensure Gibraltar’s interests are properly taken into account. The first meeting of the UK-Gibraltar Ministerial Forum on EU Exit took place on 7 December 2016, with Department for Exiting the EU and Foreign and Commonwealth Office Ministers taking part alongside the Chief Minister of Gibraltar. This followed a meeting the Parliamentary Under Secretary of State at the Department for Exiting the EU (Mr Robin Walker) chaired with the Gibraltarian Chief Minister and business and union representatives on 1 November 2016. In addition, officials continue to be in frequent contact with their Gibraltarian counterparts. The Government is committed to continued close working with the Government of Gibraltar.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657753/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-20T15:54:54.803Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657753/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657753/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-12-13","Gibraltar: Brexit","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what discussions they have held with the government of Gibraltar regarding the UK's plans to leave the EU; and whether they plan to have due regard to the views of the people of Gibraltar as expressed in the referendum.","false","Biography information for Lord Jones of Cheltenham",,"Lord Jones of Cheltenham","HL4072"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657754","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-28","<p>The UK has no doubt about its sovereignty over the Falkland Islands and surrounding maritime areas. The principle of and the right of the Falkland Islanders to self-determination as enshrined in the UN Charter and in Article 1 of the two UN Covenants on human rights means there can be no dialogue on sovereignty unless the Falkland Islanders so wish. The UK Government will always support the right of the Falkland Islanders to determine their own future and we have consistently reiterated this to Argentina.</p><p>The UK is already a full member of the World Trade Organisation.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657754/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-28T13:21:43.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657754/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657754/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-13","Falkland Islands: Sovereignty","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what discussions they have held with the governments of the Falkland Islands and Argentina regarding the desire of the Islanders to remain British; and what assessment they have made of the impact that the territorial dispute will have on the UK becoming a full member of the World Trade Organisation.","false","Biography information for Lord Jones of Cheltenham",,"Lord Jones of Cheltenham","HL4073"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657755","Department of Health","false","2016-12-15","<p>The Prime Minister and Secretary of State for Health have made it clear that they wish for European Union (EU) citizens, including those working in health and social care, to remain in the United Kingdom once the UK has left the EU, and that this would only not be possible if British citizens’ rights in European member states were not protected in return. The Government is working hard to achieve that outcome.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657755/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-15T16:13:47.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657755/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657755/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-13","NHS: Migrant Workers","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assurances they intend to give to NHS employees who were born in other EU member states that they will be able to continue working in the NHS following the UK's withdrawal from the EU.","false","Biography information for Lord Jones of Cheltenham",,"Lord Jones of Cheltenham","HL4074"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657756","Department of Health","false","2016-12-21","<p>The number of National Health Service employees who were born in other European Union (EU) member states is not collected.</p><p> </p><p>NHS Digital publishes data on the nationality of staff working in the NHS in England. Nationality is self-reported, the value entered by an individual, and therefore may reflect their cultural heritage rather than their country of birth. As at September 2016, of those NHS employees who declared a nationality, 59,796 were from an EU member state other than the United Kingdom.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657756/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-21T12:34:08.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657756/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657756/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-13","NHS: Migrant Workers","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many NHS employees were born in other EU member states.","false","Biography information for Lord Jones of Cheltenham",,"Lord Jones of Cheltenham","HL4075"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657757","Home Office","false","2017-01-09","<p>The Prime Minister has been clear that she wants to protect the status of EU nationals already living in the UK, and the only circumstances in which that wouldn’t be possible is if British citizens’ rights in other EU Member States were not protected in return.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657757/answer",,,,,,"2017-01-09T13:12:52.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657757/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657757/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-12-13","Immigration: EU Nationals","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assurances they intend to give to UK citizens' spouses and civil partners who were born in another EU member state that they will be able to remain in the UK indefinitely.","false","Biography information for Lord Jones of Cheltenham",,"Lord Jones of Cheltenham","HL4076"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657758","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-12-22","<p>The Ministry of Justice’s intention is for policy records created in 1997 and 1998 to be reviewed in 2019 for transfer to The National Archives in 2020. This is in accordance with the deadline specified by the Public Records (Transfer to the Public Record Office) (Transitional and Saving Provisions) Order 2012.</p>",,"Lord Henley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657758/answer",,,,,"HL4028","2016-12-22T11:52:54.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657758/answer","Biography information for Lord Henley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657758/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-12-13","Human Rights Act 1998","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when they intend to arrange for the publication, under the 20-year rule, of official records relating to the preparation and passage of the Human Rights Act 1998.","false","Biography information for Lord Lester of Herne Hill",,"Lord Lester of Herne Hill","HL4077"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657759","Department for Education","false","2016-12-21","<p>The EPI report fails to recognise the fact that the government’s proposals are about creating more good school places for more parents in more parts of the country by giving them more choice. Our proposals to expand the number of good school places available to parents will help more young people have the chance to go as far as their talents will take them.</p><p>Faith schools are among the highest performing schools in the country, with more primary and secondary faith schools judged good or outstanding than their non-faith counterparts[1]. Faith schools are popular with parents and the removal of the 50% faith cap will enable the establishment of even more good schools.</p><p> </p><p>[1]<em>Ofsted official statistics: Maintained schools and academies inspections and outcomes as at 31 March 2016</em> shows faith schools are more likely to be <em>good</em> or <em>outstanding</em> as compared to non-faith schools (89% as compared to 86% at primary; 81% as compared to 75% at secondary).</p><p> </p>",,"Viscount Younger of Leckie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657759/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-21T17:20:27.78Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657759/answer","Biography information for Viscount Younger of Leckie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657759/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-12-13","Faith Schools: Admissions","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the proposal to drop the 50 per cent cap on religious selection in faith schools, what consideration they have given to the finding of the Education Policy Institute, in its report <i>Faith Schools, Pupil Performance and Social Selection</i>, published in December, that the average faith school admits fewer pupils from poor backgrounds than the average non-faith school.","false","Biography information for Baroness Lister of Burtersett",,"Baroness Lister of Burtersett","HL4078"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657760","Home Office","false","2017-01-09","<p>I am sorry but we do not have this information. These cases are decided in individual overseas territories, and information on refusals is not readily available. To obtain these figures would require each territory to go through individual records and so would result in disproportionate cost.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657760/answer",,,,,,"2017-01-09T13:13:28.3Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657760/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657760/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-12-13","British Nationality","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answers by Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon on 25 April (HL7517) and 4 May (HL8199), prior to 1 July 2006, how many citizenship by descent applications were denied to individuals of British Overseas Territories descent wishing to register as British Overseas Territories citizens, where the reason for the denial was that the applicant was born to an unmarried father who at the time of the applicant’s birth held British Dependent Territories citizenship and who then automatically gained full British citizenship under the British Overseas Territories Act 2002.","false","Biography information for Baroness Lister of Burtersett",,"Baroness Lister of Burtersett","HL4079"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657761","Home Office","false","2016-12-22","<p>Following a court order dated 2 December 2016 in the case of R (on the application of Medical Justice) v the Secretary of State for the Home Department, in respect of the Home Office policy on adults at risk in immigration detention, the Home Office has reverted to the pre-12 September definition of torture in the context of immigration detention, until the Court reaches its final judgment in the case. As court proceedings are ongoing it would not be appropriate to comment on the statement from the Royal College of Psychiatrists.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657761/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-22T13:59:21.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657761/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657761/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-12-13","Immigrants: Detainees","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they intend to change their revised definition of torture issued on 12 September, in the light of position statement PS07/16 of the Royal College of Psychiatrists on the definition of torture in the context of immigration detention policy, issued in December.","false","Biography information for Lord Ramsbotham",,"Lord Ramsbotham","HL4080"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657762","Home Office","false","2017-01-09","<p>Since the publication of the Government’s response to Stephen Shaw’s Report into the welfare in detention of vulnerable persons on 14 January, work has been ongoing to design a more effective case management process to replace the existing method of reviewing detention.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657762/answer",,,,,,"2017-01-09T13:09:16.113Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657762/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657762/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-12-13","Immigrants: Detainees","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what progress has been made in introducing individual removals plans as outlined in their response to the independent review into the welfare in detention of vulnerable persons, published on 14 January.","false","Biography information for Lord Ramsbotham",,"Lord Ramsbotham","HL4081"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657763","Home Office","false","2017-01-09","<p>We are currently working with the Ministry of Justice, Her Majesty’s Court Service and the First-tier Tribunal to implement the Secretary of State’s duty to arrange consideration of bail, as set out in paragraph 11 of Schedule 10 to the Immigration Act 2016. This is just one part of a large number of changes necessary to implement the wider immigration bail provisions in Schedule 10 and will be commenced alongside those other provisions in due course.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657763/answer",,,,,,"2017-01-09T13:09:53.223Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657763/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657763/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-12-13","Immigration Bail","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when they intend to bring into force paragraph 11 of Schedule 10 to the Immigration Act 2016 regarding bail hearings for individuals in immigration detention.","false","Biography information for Lord Ramsbotham",,"Lord Ramsbotham","HL4082"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657764","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-12-23","<p>Eight social care authorities chose not to use the adult social care precept in 2016-17. They were: Stoke-on-Trent and 7 London Boroughs (City, Kensington &amp; Chelsea, Hammersmith &amp; Fulham, Ealing, Hillingdon, Hounslow and Merton).</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657764/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-23T14:52:52.593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657764/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657764/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-12-13","Social Services: Finance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government which local authorities in England with responsibilities for adult social care will not use, in the financial year 2016–17, their power to increase their council tax precept by 2 per cent to pay for such care services.","false","Biography information for Lord Warner",,"Lord Warner","HL4083"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657765","Home Office","false","2016-12-23","<p>As a result of the referendum on the UK’s membership of the EU on 23 June, the Government is considering it’s approach to the application of the JHA Opt-in and will inform the Parliamentary Scrutiny Committees once the Government has completed its consideration.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657765/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-23T13:07:42.58Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657765/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657765/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-12-13","EU Justice and Home Affairs","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government why they have not yet responded to the report by the EU Justice Sub-Committee, <i>The UK’s opt-in Protocol: implications of the Government’s approach</i>, published on 24 March 2015; and when they plan to issue the response.","false","Biography information for Baroness Kennedy of The Shaws",,"Baroness Kennedy of The Shaws","HL4084"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657766","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-12-22","<p>Sir Oliver Heald wrote on 30 November concerning the Government’s response to Lord Boswell in his capacity as Chair of the EU Committee. In his letter, Sir Oliver said that the Government is currently considering human rights reform in the context of the future constitutional framework of the United Kingdom following the vote to leave the EU, and is therefore not in a position to provide a substantive response to the Sub-Committee’s report at this time.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657766/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-22T13:02:19.563Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657766/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657766/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-12-13","Bill of Rights","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government why they have not yet responded to the report by the EU Justice Sub-Committee, <i>The UK, the EU and a British Bill of Rights</i>, published on 9 May 2016; and when they plan to issue the response.","false","Biography information for Baroness Kennedy of The Shaws",,"Baroness Kennedy of The Shaws","HL4085"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657767","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-12-29","<p>Until exit negotiations are concluded, the UK remains a full member of the European Union and all the rights and obligations of EU membership remain in force. During this period the Government will continue to negotiate, implement and apply EU legislation, including in relation to any changes to waste legislation.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657767/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-29T12:20:18.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657767/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657767/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-12-13","Waste Management: EU Law","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government<i>, </i>further to the Written Answer by Lord Gardiner of Kimble on 29 November (HL3318), whether they will transpose into UK law any changes to EU waste legislation which are made before the UK leaves the European Union<i>.</i>","false","Biography information for Baroness Jones of Whitchurch",,"Baroness Jones of Whitchurch","HL4086"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657768","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-23","<p>The Government will continue to invest in the British Council, which plays a critical role in developing international cultural relations and delivering programmes around the world which support economic and social development; help strengthen institutions, good governance and civil society; encourage debate and dialogue; and develop creativity and the arts.</p><p>The British Council has worked successfully with European neighbours for over eighty years. We have no plans at present to increase grant funding to the British Council, but will continue to support them as they find ways to work in partnership with European countries and with EU institutions to create opportunities, build connections and engender trust.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657768/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-23T12:52:53.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657768/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657768/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-13","British Council: Finance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they intend to increase funding for the British Council, in the light of the UK's exit from the European Union and the British Council's role in, and potential for, developing strong relationships with future trading allies through cultural diplomacy and soft power.","false","Biography information for Baroness Brown of Cambridge",,"Baroness Brown of Cambridge","HL4087"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657769","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-12-22","<p>The International Holocaust Remembrance Alliance (IHRA) working definition of anti-Semitism adopted by Her Majesty’s Government does not preclude criticism of Israel. As the definition makes clear, criticism of Israel similar to that levelled against any other country cannot be regarded as anti-Semitic.</p><p>The full text of the working definition of anti-Semitism and examples (attached) can be found</p><p>at: <a href="http://european-forum-on-antisemitism.org/report/working-definition-antisemitism-ihra" target="_blank">http://european-forum-on-antisemitism.org/report/working-definition-antisemitism-ihra</a></p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657769/answer","pressreleasedocumentantisemitism.pdf","pressreleasedocumentantisemitism.pdf","Anti Semitism","Anti Semitism",,"2016-12-22T16:21:11.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657769/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657769/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-12-13","Antisemitism","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether the proposed official definition of anti-semitism will include criticism of the government of Israel.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL4088"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657770","Department for International Trade","false","2016-12-20","<p><strong>The value of trade in goods between Scotland and Israel was £75 million in 2015 (Source: HM Revenue and Customs Regional Trade Statistics database). This does not include services, which will make this figure considerably higher. </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong>Israel is an important trading partner for the UK and we are committed to further strengthening our important trade relationship.</strong></p>",,"Lord Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657770/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-20T16:44:12.26Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657770/answer","Biography information for Lord Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657770/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-12-13","Overseas Trade: Israel","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what was the value of trade between Scotland and Israel in 2015; and what steps they are taking to further strengthen ties between Scotland and Israel.","false","Biography information for Lord McInnes of Kilwinning",,"Lord McInnes of Kilwinning","HL4089"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657771","Department for Transport","false","2016-12-21","<p>Based on the assumption that ‘Hybrid’ relates to the Bi-mode trains (i.e. those using both diesel and electric traction power), we can confirm that of the 65 sets allocated to East Coast, the proportions will be 23 Bi-modes and 42 Electric sets.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657771/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-21T13:58:38.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657771/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657771/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-12-13","East Coast Railway Line","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what proportion of the new InterCity train sets allocated to the East Coast franchise will be (1) hybrid trains and (2) electric trains.","false","Biography information for Lord Shipley",,"Lord Shipley","HL4090"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657772","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-12-19","<p>As with all equipment projects, the cost and schedule of the Power Improvement Project will be set at the main investment decision. Disclosing our planning assumptions prior to this point would compromise the Ministry of Defence's negotiating position and therefore be prejudicial to our commercial interests.</p>",,"Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657772/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-19T16:06:20.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657772/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657772/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-12-13","Type 45 Destroyers","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government by what date the intercooler and generator problems on all T45 destroyers will have been resolved.","false","Biography information for Lord West of Spithead",,"Lord West of Spithead","HL4091"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657773","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-12-19","<p>All Type 45 Destroyers remain in the operational cycle and continue to be routinely deployed in support of national interests.</p>",,"Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657773/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-19T16:07:18.033Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657773/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657773/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-12-13","Type 45 Destroyers","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they consider that the T45 destroyers are fully operational and could be deployed with system certainty in war.","false","Biography information for Lord West of Spithead",,"Lord West of Spithead","HL4092"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657774","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-12-19","<p>The date for the naming ceremony of the 7th Astute Class submarine is not planned to be scheduled until nearer the time of its handover to the Royal Navy, which is expected to be in 2024.</p>",,"Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657774/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-19T16:07:02.12Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657774/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657774/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-12-13","Astute Class Submarines","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is the planned date for the naming ceremony for the 7th Astute-class submarine.","false","Biography information for Lord West of Spithead",,"Lord West of Spithead","HL4093"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657775","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-12-19","<p>The Strategic Defence and Security Review 2015 reaffirmed the Government's plans for seven Astute Class submarines and four ballistic missile submarines, of which the first of class has been named Dreadnought.</p>",,"Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657775/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-19T16:40:19.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657775/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657775/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-12-13","Astute Class Submarines","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they have taken to assess whether an 8th Astute class submarine could be built prior to the first successor submarine being named.","false","Biography information for Lord West of Spithead",,"Lord West of Spithead","HL4094"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657776","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-12-22","The Department for Exiting the European Union (DExEU) has responsibility for overseeing negotiations to leave the EU and establishing the future relationship between the UK and the EU. The Ministry of Justice, which has responsibility for civil law instruments such as the Rome I Regulation, has been working closely with DExEU to consider options for the future relationship between the UK and the EU. We will work to ensure the best outcome for the UK, including its consumers and businesses.",,"Viscount Younger of Leckie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657776/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-22T11:53:27.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657776/answer","Biography information for Viscount Younger of Leckie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657776/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-12-13","Contracts: EU Law","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they intend to negotiate for the UK's continued participation in those aspects of the Rome I Regulation which require a contract between a business and a consumer to be governed by the law of the country where the consumer lives; and if so, whether they will convert the rules set out in Rome I into domestic law by including them in the legislation required to withdraw from the EU.","false","Biography information for Baroness Hayter of Kentish Town",,"Baroness Hayter of Kentish Town","HL4095"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657777","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-12-22","<p>The Department for Exiting the European Union (DExEU) has responsibility for overseeing negotiations to leave the EU and establishing the future relationship between the UK and the EU. The Ministry of Justice, which has responsibility for civil judicial cooperation legal instruments such as the Brussels I recast Regulation, has been working closely with DExEU to consider options for the future relationship between the UK and the EU. We will work to ensure the best outcome for the UK, including its consumers and businesses.</p>",,"Lord Henley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657777/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-22T11:54:26.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657777/answer","Biography information for Lord Henley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657777/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-12-13","Civil Proceedings: EU Law","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they intend to negotiate the UK's continued participation in those aspects of the Brussels I framework which provide that civil and commercial judgments are recognised and enforced throughout the EU, and provide for consumers to sue or defend themselves in domestic courts and have any judgment enforced across the EU.","false","Biography information for Baroness Hayter of Kentish Town",,"Baroness Hayter of Kentish Town","HL4096"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657778","Department for Transport","false","2016-12-21","<p>We want the best deal possible for the UK upon leaving the EU. The Department for Transport which has policy responsibility for motor insurance and the Ministry of Justice which leads on civil judicial cooperation (including the Brussels I recast Regulation), have been working closely with the Department for Exiting the European Union to consider options for the future relationship between the UK and the EU.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657778/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-21T14:02:33.693Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657778/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657778/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-12-13","Motor Vehicles: Insurance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in pursuing the negotiations for Brexit, whether they will maintain the UK's reciprocity under the Brussels 1 Regulation and the Motor Insurance Directive to allow victims of accidents to use their domestic courts to pursue insurance claims after an accident in another member state.","false","Biography information for Baroness Hayter of Kentish Town",,"Baroness Hayter of Kentish Town","HL4097"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657779","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-21","<p>Departments are currently working with stakeholders to understand the impacts that withdrawal from the EU will have on businesses, consumers and other economic actors - we will work to ensure the best possible outcome for UK consumers.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657779/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-21T12:32:39.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657779/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657779/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-13","Consumers: Protection","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in pursuing the negotiations for Brexit, whether they will negotiate to maintain the UK's membership of the Consumer Protection Cooperation Network and the Rapid Alert System.","false","Biography information for Baroness Hayter of Kentish Town",,"Baroness Hayter of Kentish Town","HL4098"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657780","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-19","<p>Departments are currently working with stakeholders to understand the impacts that withdrawal from the EU will have on businesses, consumers and other economic actors - we will work to ensure the best possible outcome for UK consumers.</p><p> </p><p>The Government will set out its broad plans before triggering Article 50 by the end of next March.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657780/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-19T16:05:14.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657780/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657780/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-13","Package Holidays: EU Law","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in pursuing the negotiations for Brexit, whether they will seek to retain the ability of consumers to obtain both financial and injury compensation through the Package Travel Directive 1990 and the Package Travel Directive 2015.","false","Biography information for Baroness Hayter of Kentish Town",,"Baroness Hayter of Kentish Town","HL4099"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657781","Department for Transport","false","2016-12-21","<p>The Government is considering the impacts of the decision to leave the European Union, including future arrangements for existing legislation. Until the UK leaves, EU law continues to apply, so we continue to comply with the existing directives and regulations, such as the common rules on compensation and assistance under Regulation (EC) 261/2004.</p><p> </p><p>This government remains committed to putting passengers at the heart of our transport policy and ensuring we have the right regime for passenger rights in place.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657781/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-21T11:52:28.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657781/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657781/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-12-13","Aviation: Compensation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in pursuing the negotiations for Brexit, whether they will seek to retain the ability of passengers flying in the EU to claim compensation for delays and cancellations through EC Regulation 261/2004.","false","Biography information for Baroness Hayter of Kentish Town",,"Baroness Hayter of Kentish Town","HL4100"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657782","Home Office","false","2017-01-09","<p>The Home Office is committed to publishing data in an orderly way as part of the regular quarterly Immigration Statistics, in line with the Code of Practice for Official Statistics.</p><p>Latest statistics published on 01 December confirmed that a total of 4,414 Syrians have been resettled under the scheme since it began, 4,162 of these arriving in the 12 months to the end of September 2016.</p><p>Religious affiliation of those resettled under the Syrian Vulnerable Persons Resettlement (VPR) scheme is monitored, but not routinely reported.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657782/answer",,,,,,"2017-01-09T13:12:05.58Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657782/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657782/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-12-13","Refugees: Syria","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many people have been resettled under the Syrian vulnerable persons resettlement programme; and how many, as a number and as a percentage, came from the Christian or Yazidi communities.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL4101"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657783","Home Office","false","2016-12-22","<p>We are clear that our scheme will prioritise the most vulnerable refugees, and that is why under the Syrian Vulnerable Persons Resettlement (VPR) scheme the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) identifies refugees for resettlement using its established vulnerability criteria. The seven vulnerability criteria used by the UNHCR are Legal and or Physical Protection Needs; Survivors of Torture and/or Violence; Medical Needs; Women and Girls at Risk; Family Reunification; Children and Adolescents at Risk and Lack of Foreseeable Alternative Durable Solutions.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657783/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-22T14:02:32.01Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657783/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657783/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-12-13","Refugees: Syria","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what account is taken of the resolution of the House of Commons on the Daesh genocide of minorities (HC Deb, 20 April, col 608) when prioritising victims of genocide for resettlement under the Syrian vulnerable persons resettlement programme.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL4102"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657784","Cabinet Office","false","2016-12-20","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>",,"Baroness Chisholm of Owlpen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657784/answer","Reply to Baroness Wolf (HL4103-HL4105) AD3 (1) (1) (1).pdf","Reply to Baroness Wolf (HL4103-HL4105) AD3 (1) (1) (1).pdf","UKSA response to HL4103, HL4104,HL4105","UKSA response to HL4103, HL4104,HL4105","HL4104 ; HL4105","2016-12-20T16:45:27.563Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657784/answer","Biography information for Baroness Chisholm of Owlpen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657784/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-12-13","Statistics","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many UK regulators follow the UK Statistics Authority Code of Practice for Official Statistics in their collection and publication of statistics.","false","Biography information for Baroness Wolf of Dulwich",,"Baroness Wolf of Dulwich","HL4103"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657785","Cabinet Office","false","2016-12-20","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>",,"Baroness Chisholm of Owlpen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657785/answer","Reply to Baroness Wolf (HL4103-HL4105) AD3 (1) (1) (1).pdf","Reply to Baroness Wolf (HL4103-HL4105) AD3 (1) (1) (1).pdf","UKSA response to HL4103, HL4104,HL4105","UKSA response to HL4103, HL4104,HL4105","HL4103 ; HL4105","2016-12-20T16:45:27.61Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657785/answer","Biography information for Baroness Chisholm of Owlpen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657785/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-12-13","Statistics","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many UK regulators publish statistical releases that have National Statistics status.","false","Biography information for Baroness Wolf of Dulwich",,"Baroness Wolf of Dulwich","HL4104"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657786","Cabinet Office","false","2016-12-20","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>",,"Baroness Chisholm of Owlpen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657786/answer","Reply to Baroness Wolf (HL4103-HL4105) AD3 (1) (1) (1).pdf","Reply to Baroness Wolf (HL4103-HL4105) AD3 (1) (1) (1).pdf","UKSA response to HL4103, HL4104,HL4105","UKSA response to HL4103, HL4104,HL4105","HL4103 ; HL4104","2016-12-20T16:45:27.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657786/answer","Biography information for Baroness Chisholm of Owlpen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657786/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-12-13","Statistics","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government which UK regulators are, as part of their statutory remit, required to follow the UK Statistics Authority Code of Practice for Official Statistics.","false","Biography information for Baroness Wolf of Dulwich",,"Baroness Wolf of Dulwich","HL4105"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657787","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-28","<p>​The Overseas Territories (OTs) are responsible for setting their own rates of taxation, and the Government respects their right to compete in this area. All relevant OTs have committed to greater tax transparency by adopting the new global standard for the automatic exchange of financial account information, which will combat tax evasion. Her Majesty's Revenue and Customs have begun to receive information on the accounts held in OTs by UK taxpayers, one year earlier than from the rest of the world.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657787/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-28T13:22:21.72Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657787/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657787/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-13","British Overseas Territories: Taxation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many British territories have special tax regimes and what action they are taking to address this.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL4106"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657788","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-20","<p>The Consumer Rights Act (CRA) came into force 1<sup>st</sup> October 2015. The act has given Trading Standards Officers (TSOs) greater flexibility to respond to breaches of consumer law, such as seeking redress for consumers who have suffered harm.</p><p> </p><p>TSOs have a range of additional powers dependent upon the legislation they are enforcing. These include the power to require traders to produce documents relating to their business and powers to seize and detain goods and documents in certain circumstances.</p><p> </p><p>Following responses to a Call for Evidence run in spring 2016 on Terms and Conditions and Civil Enforcement, the Department is considereing the strength of Local Authority Trading Standards Services’ powers in enforcing consumer protection law such as that on unfair contract terms. The department will publish their response to this Call for Evidence in due course.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657788/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-20T13:55:30.683Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657788/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657788/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-13","Trading Standards","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment have they made of the adequacy of the powers of trading standards officers.","true","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL4107"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657789","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-01-13","<p>The Government is satisfied that current legislation provides local authorities with the necessary powers to enforce the provisions of food law and local environment regulations.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657789/answer",,,,,,"2017-01-13T14:19:27.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657789/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657789/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-12-13","Environmental Health","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment have they made of the adequacy of the powers of environmental health officers.","true","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL4108"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657790","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-12-21","<p>The new Holocaust Memorial will stand as a statement of our commitment to remember the Holocaust and, crucially as a statement of determination to stand up to prejudice and hatred of all kinds. While the focus of the Memorial will be on the persecution and murder of 6 millions European Jews, it will also appropriately represent the experiences of the Roma/Sinti and of all groups persecuted by the Nazis. It is therefore vital that representatives of all victims of Nazi persecution are able to have their say on what the Memorial looks like.</p><p>Once the shortlisted designs are received for the Memorial, the UK Holocaust Memorial Foundation will hold exhibitions and consultations all around the United Kingdom, providing all people with an opportunity to connect.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657790/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-21T13:37:08.747Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657790/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657790/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-12-13","World War II: Genocide","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth on 12 December (HL3686), when the consultation on the design competition for the Holocaust memorial will begin, and which Roma organisations will be consulted on the competition.","false","Biography information for Baroness Whitaker",,"Baroness Whitaker","HL4109"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657791","Department for Education","false","2017-01-09","<p>We are committed to ensuring that apprenticeships are as accessible as possible to all people from all backgrounds, including young people from Gypsy and Traveller communities. Apprenticeships give young people the chance to build a better future by taking their first step on the employment ladder and they give those already in work the opportunity to progress further. We are encouraging a wide range of people from all backgrounds into apprenticeships through our ‘Get In Go Far’ campaign which is aimed at 14-24 year-olds, their parents, teachers and employers. We are increasing numbers of traineeships to further support young people into apprenticeships and further work.</p><p> </p><p>In the apprenticeship funding policy published in October, we announced extra payments for 16-18 year olds and 19-24 year olds formerly in care or with an Education, Health and Care Plan. Employers and providers will receive a payment of £1,000 to support additional costs associated with these apprentices.</p><p> </p><p>We want to ensure we overcome barriers so all can access apprenticeships and support those from disadvantaged areas with over £60m of funding. Providers will receive an additional £600 for training an apprentice who lives in one of the top 10% of deprived areas (as per the Index of Multiple Deprivation), £300 for any apprentice who lives in the next 10% of deprived areas (the 11-20% range), and £200 for those in the next 7% (the 21-27% range). This will be in place for one year whilst we review our approach to supporting disadvantaged apprentices; ensuring apprenticeships provide equal opportunity to all, regardless of their circumstances.</p>",,"Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657791/answer",,,,,,"2017-01-09T17:52:09.497Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657791/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657791/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-12-13","Apprentices: Travellers","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Nash on 12 December (HL3767), how they are encouraging young people from the Gypsy and Traveller communities into apprenticeships through the Get In Go Far campaign and by other means.","false","Biography information for Baroness Whitaker",,"Baroness Whitaker","HL4110"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657801","Attorney General","false","2016-12-19","<p>It is not the SFO’s policy to disclose information about the source of what are confidential reports about an alleged criminal offence, or the details of a report. Releasing such information could potentially compromise criminal investigations or prosecutions and may also discourage other individuals from reporting crimes to the SFO.</p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657801/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-19T13:46:08.183Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657801/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657801/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2016-12-13","Rolls Royce: Corruption","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, pursuant to the Answer of 25 October 2016 to Question 49510, from whom the Serious Fraud Office first received information concerning allegations of bribery and corruption at Rolls Royce.","false","Biography information for Dame Margaret Hodge","Barking","Margaret Hodge","57311"
