"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657817","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-12-16","<p>At the end of November 2016, 4,792 Cyber Essentials certificates had been awarded, of which it is estimated 3,682 have been awarded to small and medium sized businesses, 77% of the total. The number of certificates issued to enterprises in each category is estimated at: micro 1,237; small 1,350; medium 1,095; and large 1,110.</p><p> </p><p>The Government, including the National Cyber Security Centre, is working on a range of measures to drive further and faster adoption of the scheme, including strengthening the existing requirement for Government suppliers which handle sensitive data or provide certain ICT products and services to hold a Cyber Essentials certificate. As such, we expect the rate of adoption to increase significantly throughout the coming year.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657817/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-16T08:30:16.497Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657817/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657817/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-12-13","Cybercrime: Small Businesses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, pursuant to the Answer of 17 October 2016 to Quesiton 48089, what progress has been made in signing up small and medium-sized businesses to the cyber essentials programme; and what estimate she has made of the number of such businesses to be signed up in 2017.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","57370"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657818","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-12-16","<p>A review of gaming machines and social responsibility measures (previously called the Triennial Review) began with a 6 week call for evidence on 24 October, closing on 4 December. As part of this, we sought evidence on Fixed-Odds Betting Terminals and gambling advertising. The review generated a lot of interest from the general public, as well as from a variety of interest groups, local authorities, trade bodies and industry. We are now looking in depth at the evidence and aim to publish our findings and any proposals in spring 2017.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657818/answer",,,,,"57401 ; 57524","2016-12-16T08:31:56.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657818/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657818/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-12-13","Gaming Machines and Social Responsibility Measures Review","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, when she plans to publish the results of the call for evidence on the Review of Gaming Machines and Social Responsibility Measures.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","57400"
