"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657883","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-16","<p>The British High Commission in Yaoundé is following the situation closely and has called for restraint and encouraged dialogue. The High Commissioner chaired a meeting with the US, French, Canadians and the EU on 1 December to discuss this matter. The UK supports the independent investigation by the National Commission for Human Rights and Freedoms into the violence and deaths in Bamenda. The UK believes that all parties have a responsibility to uphold and protect the peace and stability of Cameroon and that legal and peaceful means should be used to voice any grievances. The violence has abated and we hope for a swift and peaceful resolution of this matter.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657883/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-16T14:48:33.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657883/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657883/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-13","Cameroon: Courts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with his counterpart in the government of Cameroon on French-speaking judges presiding in courts in the English-speaking north-west and south-west regions of Cameroon.","false","Biography information for Rob Marris","Wolverhampton South West","Rob Marris","57389"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657884","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-16","<p>The British High Commission in Yaoundé is following the situation closely and has called for restraint and encouraged dialogue. The High Commissioner chaired a meeting with the US, French, Canadians and the EU on 1 December to discuss this matter. The UK supports the independent investigation by the National Commission for Human Rights and Freedoms into the violence and deaths in Bamenda. The UK believes that all parties have a responsibility to uphold and protect the peace and stability of Cameroon and that legal and peaceful means should be used to voice any grievances. The violence has abated and we hope for a swift and peaceful resolution of this matter.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657884/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-16T14:48:03.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657884/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657884/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-13","Cameroon: Demonstrations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with his counterpart in Cameroon on reported injuries and deaths of protestors during strikes by teachers and lawyers in December 2016 in the north-west and south-west English-speaking regions of Cameroon.","false","Biography information for Rob Marris","Wolverhampton South West","Rob Marris","57390"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657885","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-22","<p>Ministers and officials have raised Mrs Nazanin Zaghari-Ratcliffe's detention repeatedly, at all levels, with the Iranian government. The Prime Minister, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Maidenhead (Mrs May), and The Foreign Secretary, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Uxbridge and South Ruislip (Mr Johnson), raised Mrs Zaghari- Ratcliffe's case with their Iranian counterparts during the UN General Assembly in September. The Prime Minister followed up her concerns in writing to President Rouhani on 3 October. I also met with the Iranian Ambassador and Mrs Zaghari-Ratcliffe's husband, Richard Ratcliffe, on 7 December, and we will continue to raise these cases with the Iranian Government at every available opportunity.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657885/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-22T14:39:45.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657885/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657885/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-13","Nazanin Zaghari-Ratcliffe","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with his counterpart in the Iranian government on the detention of Nazanin Zaghari-Ratcliffe.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","Wycombe","Steve Baker","57376"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657886","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-20","<p>The British High Commission in Yaoundé is following the situation closely and has called for restraint and encouraged dialogue. The High Commissioner chaired a meeting with the US, French, Canadians and the EU on 1 December to discuss this matter. The UK supports the independent investigation by the National Commission for Human Rights and Freedoms into the violence and deaths in Bamenda. The UK believes that all parties have a responsibility to uphold and protect the peace and stability of Cameroon and that legal and peaceful means should be used to voice any grievances. The violence has abated and we hope for a swift and peaceful resolution of this matter.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657886/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-20T14:49:53.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657886/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657886/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-13","Cameroon: Schools","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with his counterpart in the government of Cameroon on French-speaking teachers teaching in schools in the English-speaking Northwest and Southwest regions of Cameroon.","false","Biography information for Rob Marris","Wolverhampton South West","Rob Marris","57354"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657887","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-16","<p>Reports that Gambian security forces loyal to President Jammeh have taken over the offices of Independent Election Commission (IEC) are a real cause for concern. Tensions remain high following President Jammeh's legal challenge to the Supreme Court to annul the election results and the increased military checkpoints on the streets. We have urged all regional and international partners to continue to impress on Mr Jammeh that he must respect the will of the people and ensure a peaceful handover of power to President-elect Barrow and the incoming Government.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657887/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-16T14:53:39.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657887/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657887/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-13","Gambia: Elections","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of (a) the security situation and (b) state of democracy in the Gambia following reports that Gambian security forces have taken over electoral commission headquarters and have prevented employees from entering.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","57394"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657888","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-16","We welcome the clear, unified statement of the UN Security Council on 10 December calling for the Gambian election results to be respected, as well as the efforts of Economic Community Of West African States to impress on President Jammeh the need to respect the will of the people and ensure a peaceful handover of power to President-elect Barrow. The UK is working with all international partners at the UN to ensure the democratic will of the Gambian people is enacted in a peaceful manner. The UK's permanent representative to the UN is engaged on the current situation in The Gambia.","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657888/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-16T14:49:51.503Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657888/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657888/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-13","Gambia: Elections","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether he has discussed the outcome of the Gambian general election with the (a) UK's permanent representative, (b) Chinese Ambassador, (c) US Ambassador, (d) Russian Ambassador and (e) French Ambassador to the UN.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","57395"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657889","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-21","<p>UK officials have discussed the recent US announcement with their US counterparts.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657889/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-21T11:23:01.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657889/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657889/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-13","USA: Arms Trade","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether he has discussed the recent US partial cessation of weapons sales to Saudi Arabia with his US counterpart.","false","Biography information for Douglas Chapman","Dunfermline and West Fife","Douglas Chapman","57462"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657890","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-20","<p>The Foreign and Commonwealth Office and our Embassy in Bahrain continue to monitor Sheikh Ali Salman’s case closely. Embassy officials have attended every trial hearing so far. Where we have concerns we continue to raise them with the Government of Bahrain, and we continue to encourage the Government of Bahrain to deliver on its international and domestic human rights commitments.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657890/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-20T14:51:37.613Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657890/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657890/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-13","Ali Salman","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent representations he has made to the government of Bahrain on the detention of Sheikh Ali Salman.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","57417"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657891","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-20","<p>The Government continues to monitor the investigation into Giulio Regeni’s death, and we note that an Egyptian delegation visited Rome 6-7 December to discuss the investigation with the Italian authorities. The Minister for the Middle East and Africa, Her Majesty’s Ambassador to Egypt, and senior officials in London have raised Mr Regeni’s case with the Egyptian and Italian authorities, and the Prime Minister discussed the case with former Prime Minister Renzi. We stand ready to assist the Italian authorities in any further way we can.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657891/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-20T14:53:37.993Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657891/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657891/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-13","Giulio Regeni","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent progress the Government has made on its response to the murder of Giulio Regeni.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","57476"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657892","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-16","The Foreign and Commonwealth Office and our Embassy in Bahrain continute to closely monitor Mohammed Ramadan's case. We also continue to encourage the Government of Bahrain to deliver on its international and domestic human rights commitments. We have raised concerns both in public and in private, by having frank discussions including at the most senior levels. The Prime Minister, my right hon. Friend the Member for Maidenhead (Mrs May) was very clear during her recent visit that we want to see Gulf states embed international norms and see through essential reforms.","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657892/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-16T14:51:51.61Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657892/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657892/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-13","Mohamed Ramadan","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations his Department has received on the death sentence of Mohammed Ramadan in Bahrain.","false","Biography information for Mark Durkan","Foyle","Mark Durkan","57546"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657893","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-16","<p>Follwoing the bombing of the El-Boutrosiya Church in Cairo, the Prime Minister wrote a letter to the Egyptian President to convey her condolences to the victims families, as well as to the Egyptian people. Additionally, the Foreign Secretary spoke to the Egyptian Foreign Minister to express his sympathy and reiterate the UK's resolve to stand united with Egypt in defence of its people's right to live together in peace.</p><p>The British Government continues to collaborate with the Egyptian Government on a wide range of issues, including security and counter-terrosrism.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657893/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-16T14:44:08.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657893/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657893/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-13","Egypt: Bombings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will hold discussions with the Egyptian government on the recent Coptic church bomb attack in Cairo.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","57510"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657894","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-16","<p>The Government of Indonesia has confirmed that Governor Purnama will be prosecuted in accordance with Indonesian law. The UK Government remains a keen supporter of human rights in Indonesia, and it will be important that Governor Purnama’s trial is conducted to international standards and that his rights are respected in accordance with the rule of law. Our Embassy in Jakarta will continue to monitor the situation closely</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657894/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-16T13:32:57.13Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657894/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657894/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-13","Basuki Tjahaja Purnama","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will make representations to the Indonesian government on the trial of Basuki Tjahaja Purnama, the Governor of Jakarta.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","57511"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657895","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-21","<p>The Government strongly condemns the persecution of all minorities, including the targeting of people based on their beliefs. Our concerns are reflected in the latest update to the Foreign and Commonwealth Office annual human rights report.</p><p>We regularly raise our concerns about the protection of minority communities, including religious minorities, with the Pakistani Government at a senior level. During his visit to Pakistan in November, the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Uxbridge and South Ruislip (Boris Johnson), raised religious tolerance and the importance of safeguarding the rights of all Pakistan's citizens. We continue to urge Pakistan to honour in practice its human rights obligations, including those related to religious minorities, and to uphold the rule of law.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657895/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-21T11:25:47.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657895/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657895/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-13","Pakistan: Ahmadiyya","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions his Department has had with the Pakistani High Commission on reports of increasing persecution of the Ahmadi community in Pakistan.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","57525"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657896","Department of Health","false","2016-12-20","<p>The transitional pay protection arrangements agreed with the junior doctor leadership within the British Medical Association mean that junior doctors in the higher stages of training remain on existing pay terms, including annual incremental pay increases, until 2022, which gives part-time workers more active protection of their pay than straightforward cash floor pay protection. Allowing them to continue on the existing pay system provides protection in respect of anticipated earnings for those whose career choices were made some time ago. This applies to all those in the higher stages of training, male and female.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657896/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-20T17:01:51.843Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657896/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657896/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-13","Junior Doctors: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many female junior doctors are likely to be affected by the changes in the junior doctor contract that propose six years' training before being transferred to a new pay scale.","false","Biography information for John Cryer","Leyton and Wanstead","John Cryer","57544"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657897","Department of Health","false","2016-12-19","<p>This information is not collected.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657897/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-19T16:33:57.71Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657897/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657897/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-13","Junior Doctors: Maternity Leave","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many junior doctors took maternity leave in each year of the last five years.","false","Biography information for John Cryer","Leyton and Wanstead","John Cryer","57545"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657898","Department of Health","false","2016-12-16","<p>Local councils are responsible for ensuring adequate provision of social care services for eligible users and carers in their area.</p><p> </p><p>However, social care is a key priority for this Government, and we are giving councils access to further funding to manage social care pressures in their local area across the next few years:</p><p>- Next year councils will be able to raise the precept by up to 3%, and 3% the year after (2018/19). This could raise £200 million in additional funding for adult social care in 2017/18 and over £400 million in 2018/19.</p><p>- The Government is also providing an additional £240 million to fund adult social care through the Adult Social Care Support Grant, funded by reforms to the New Homes Bonus.</p><p> </p><p>These new changes provide access to an additional £450 million for social care next year, following calls from the sector that funding was most needed in 2017/18.</p><p> </p><p>Taken together with the funding announced in the autumn 2015 Spending Review, this means that local government will have access to the funding it needs to increase social care spending every year in this Parliament. The spending review gave councils the flexibility to introduce a 2% social care precept for adult social care, and access to additional funding for adult social care worth £1.5 billion by 2019/20 through the Better Care Fund, starting in April 2017.</p><p> </p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657898/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-16T12:06:18.62Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657898/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657898/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-13","Social Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps he is taking to ensure that adequate levels of a wide range of adult social care is available in each local authority area.","false","Biography information for David Morris","Morecambe and Lunesdale","David Morris","57537"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657899","Department of Health","false","2016-12-16","<p>The Care Act 2014 requires local authorities to meet a person’s eligible needs. Where a person requires 24 hour care local authorities should arrange services to meet those needs having regard to best practice guidance for example developed by the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657899/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-16T12:05:37.503Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657899/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657899/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-13","Care Homes: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what guidelines he provides to local authorities on the commissioning of 24-hour care places for adults with severe disabilities.","false","Biography information for David Morris","Morecambe and Lunesdale","David Morris","57538"
