"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657908","Department of Health","false","2016-12-20","<p>No such discussions have taken place.</p><p> </p><p>Prescribing decisions are for clinicians taking into account their patients’ individual clinical circumstances.</p><p> </p><p>Bisphosphonates are not licensed for the treatment or prevention of secondary breast cancer. However clinicians can prescribe bisphosphonates ‘off-license’, subject to any local funding policies, if they consider them to be clinically appropriate for an individual. Current prescribing arrangements allow off-license drugs that are found to have new uses to be prescribed to patients.</p><p> </p><p>There is no legal or regulatory barrier to prescribing drugs off license. Prescribing in this way is part of normal every day clinical practice and offers benefits to a great number of patients.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657908/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-20T16:26:08.09Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657908/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657908/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-13","Breast Cancer: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what discussions his Department has had with clinicians on barriers to prescribing bisphosphonates to prevent secondary breast cancer.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","57475"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657909","Department of Health","false","2016-12-16","<p>We are informed by NHS Improvement that National Health Service trusts and foundation trusts do not specifically disclose the amount owed from private patients at the year end.</p><p> </p><p>However trusts provide NHS Improvement with data on revenue and losses in their accounts. This data for 2015/16 suggests that 99.5% of total private patient revenue billed was collected in due course.</p><p> </p><p>Any surplus generated from the treatment of private patients is reinvested by the provider for the benefit of NHS patients.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657909/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-16T14:43:11.97Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657909/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657909/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-13","NHS Trusts: Private Patients","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 5 December 2016 to Question 55033, if he will make an estimate of the level of outstanding fees from private patients.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","57479"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657910","Department of Health","false","2016-12-19","<p>NHS England does not hold information centrally on the number of beds available for parents to stay with their baby. Neonatal Critical Care Operational Delivery Networks manage neonatal units locally.</p><p>However, following a recent report by the charity BLISS which addressed the issue of beds for parents, NHS England is currently reviewing Neonatal Critical Care Units including availability of beds for parents in these units. The review is expected to report by the end of 2017.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657910/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-19T14:55:00.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657910/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657910/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-13","Baby Care Units","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what proportion of NHS Trusts have more than one bed available for overnight stays for people with babies in neonatal units.","false","Biography information for Dr Rosena Allin-Khan","Tooting","Dr Rosena Allin-Khan","57416"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657911","Department of Health","false","2016-12-16","<p>The Department does not hold this information.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657911/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-16T10:20:17.833Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657911/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657911/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-13","Dental Services: Costs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the effect of the cost of dentistry services on the number of people who seek to treat their own dental problems.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","57428"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657912","Department of Health","false","2016-12-16","<p>The implementation of the 2014 strategy to move to universal offer of Bacillus Calmette–Guérin (BCG) vaccination for all babies up to the age of one year in London has been interrupted by a global shortage of the BCG vaccine since April 2015. Public Health England has successfully secured an alternative unlicensed supply of BCG vaccine for the United Kingdom from a different manufacturer. As stocks remain restricted, NHS England has produced a protocol for delivery to those in the following priority groups:</p><p>- All infants (aged 0 to 12 months) with a parent or grandparent who was born in a country where the annual incidence of tuberculosis (TB) is 40/100,000 or greater.</p><p>- All infants (aged 0 to 12 months) living in areas of the UK where the annual incidence of TB is 40/100,000 or greater.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657912/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-16T12:32:33.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657912/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657912/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-13","Tuberculosis: Vaccination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, for what reasons TB vaccinations are not available on the NHS to children in all London boroughs; and what the requirements are for boroughs to provide TB vaccinations by the NHS.","false","Biography information for Dr Rosena Allin-Khan","Tooting","Dr Rosena Allin-Khan","57420"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657913","Department of Health","false","2016-12-16","<p>We do not routinely collect this information.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657913/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-16T13:58:37.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657913/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657913/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-13","Dental Services: Waiting Lists","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the average waiting time was for dental treatment at dental hospitals in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","57429"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657914","Department of Health","false","2016-12-16","<p>Information is not available in the format requested.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657914/answer",,,,,"57501","2016-12-16T13:56:26.72Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657914/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657914/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-13","Dental Services: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what proportion of children are registered to a dentist; and what estimate his Department has made of the average frequency with which children visited a dentist in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","57423"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657915","Department of Health","false","2016-12-19","<p>The Department has not had any recent discussions with National Ambulance Service Medical Directors on this subject.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England has advised that it is working with all ambulance services in England to ensure the right resource is allocated to the right 999 call at the right time.</p><p> </p><p>Currently the flagging of patients with long term conditions or longer term care needs is not used universally. However the development of technology to allow real-time searching of the National Health Service number as a unique patient identifier will significantly increase the value of placing ‘flags’ on patients with specific clinical needs. This will then reliably allow any attending healthcare professional to access care plans and special patient notes to help inform individual patient management. This is a component of the 2017/19 ambulance service national Commissioning Quality and Innovation framework.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657915/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-19T17:08:38.4Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657915/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657915/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-13","Neuromuscular Disorders: Ambulance Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what discussions his Department has had with National Ambulance Service Medical Directors on ensuring that the best practice system of flagging people with muscle-wasting conditions to ambulance crews in London North West and North East ambulance services is utilised across all ambulance services.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","57472"
