"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657994","Women and Equalities","false","2016-12-16","<p>The Government Equalities Office takes part in the annual Civil Service People Survey within the Department for Education. The Department’s results for 2016 were published on GOV.UK on Tuesday 6 December.</p><p>The Equality and Human Rights Commission is an independent body and is responsible for its own staff management, including conducting surveys of its staff. I have therefore asked the Chief Executive of the Commission to write to the Hon. Member with the information requested and will place a copy of the letter in the Libraries of both Houses.</p><p> </p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657994/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-16T14:15:37.803Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657994/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657994/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2016-12-13","Staff: Surveys","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, whether there is an annual survey of staff in the (a) Government Equalities Office and (b) Equality and Human Rights Commission.","false","Biography information for Paula Sherriff","Dewsbury","Paula Sherriff","57301"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657995","Women and Equalities","false","2016-12-16","<p>The table below shows the average hourly earnings of the Department for Education (DfE) staff, including the Government Equalities Office (GEO) staff, by a) female b) male c) BME and d) non-BME.</p><p>Average Earnings of DfE Staff (including GEO)</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Nov-16</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Female</p></td><td><p>£20.61</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Male</p></td><td><p>£21.97</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>BME</p></td><td><p>£18.98</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Non-BME</p></td><td><p>£21.93</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The following table shows the average hourly earnings of GEO staff by a) female and b) male.</p><p>Average earnings of GEO Staff</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Nov-16</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Female</p></td><td><p>£24.11</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Male</p></td><td><p>£25.10</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The Department and GEO records earnings as annual salaries. In order to convert the annual salaries to hourly rates the following calculation has been used: ((Gross Basic Salary*FTE)/52)/Weekly hours.</p><p>The pay gap is lower when analysed at grade level for men and women and BME and non-BME. The gaps can be largely attributed to the fact that is greater proportions of women and BME staff of the lower pay bands.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657995/answer",,,,,"57322","2016-12-16T16:32:34.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657995/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657995/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2016-12-13","Government Equalities Office: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, what the average hourly earnings are of (a) female and (b) male employees of the Government Equalities Office.","false","Biography information for Paula Sherriff","Dewsbury","Paula Sherriff","57324"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657996","Women and Equalities","false","2016-12-20","<p>The Access to Elected Office Fund was set up to help disabled candidates meet their additional costs in standing for election. It was a three-year pilot that ran until the General Election in May 2015. No applications were made after March 2015.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657996/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-20T17:37:11.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657996/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657996/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2016-12-13","Access to Elected Office for Disabled People Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, how many applications were made to Access to Elected Office Fund 2015-16 by (a) political party, (b) gender, (c) ethnicity and (d) region; and how many such applications were (i) granted and (ii) refused.","false","Biography information for Paula Sherriff","Dewsbury","Paula Sherriff","57345"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657997","Women and Equalities","false","2016-12-20","<p>An evaluation of the Access to Elected Office pilot fund is currently being undertaken. The report from that evaluation will be published when a statement about the future of the fund is made in due course.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657997/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-20T17:37:24.693Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657997/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657997/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2016-12-13","Access to Elected Office for Disabled People Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, when she plans to (a) publish the evaluation report on the Access to Elected Office Fund and (b) make a decision on whether that Fund should continue.","false","Biography information for Paula Sherriff","Dewsbury","Paula Sherriff","57346"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657998","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-12-16","<p>I refer the honourable gentleman to the answer I previously provided on 6 December 2016 - <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2016-12-01/55848/" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2016-12-01/55848/</a></p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657998/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-16T13:43:37.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657998/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657998/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-12-13","Social Security Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment his Department has made of the financial effect on recipients of working age benefits of the benefits freeze; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","57364"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657999","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-12-16","<p>The average cost for a claimant waiting when making a call from a landline to Universal Credit is £0.41. This is based on the Average Speed to Answer of 3 minutes 27 seconds for this financial year to date.</p><p>When a claimant phones Universal Credit and the Telephony Agent (TA) has established the reason for the call, the claimant may request a call back if they cannot afford the call. In these circumstances the TA must encourage the claimant to go online if the reason for the call is to make a claim to Universal Credit.</p><p>If the claimant is considered vulnerable or suffering hardship, the TA can agree to the call back. Where the TA can ring back immediately they will do that, alternatively where this is not possible they will advise the claimant they will be called back within 3 hours and wrap up the call.</p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657999/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-16T15:04:20.92Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657999/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657999/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-12-13","Universal Credit: Telephone Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will make an assessment of the cost to claimants of the length of waiting times when making calls to his Department related to universal credits.","false","Biography information for Drew Hendry","Inverness, Nairn, Badenoch and Strathspey","Drew Hendry","57334"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/658000","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-12-16","<p>a) The Average Speed to Answer when a claimant makes a call to Universal Credit is 3 minutes 27 seconds based on this financial year to date.</p><p>b) We do not hold data specifically for calls made from hon. Member's office’s enquiring about a Universal Credit.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/658000/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-16T14:19:59.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/658000/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/658000/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-12-13","Universal Credit: Telephone Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the average call waiting time was for (a) a claimant and (b) an hon. Member's office enquiring about a universal credits claim.","false","Biography information for Drew Hendry","Inverness, Nairn, Badenoch and Strathspey","Drew Hendry","57335"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/658001","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-12-16","<p>Since 1998 the Department has occupied the majority of its accommodation under a Private Finance Initiative (PFI) known as the PRIME contract. Under the terms of this 20 year PFI, the department contracts to occupy fully serviced accommodation from its private sector partner, Telereal Trillium.</p><p> </p><p>The leases for the buildings in question are included within the provisions of this PFI arrangement and are therefore not held directly by the department. As such, the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions has had no discussions with the landlords of a) Shettleston, (b) Parkhead and (c) Easterhouse Jobcentre Plus offices.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/658001/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-16T14:42:14.213Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/658001/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/658001/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-12-13","Jobcentres: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what discussions he has had on what dates with the landlords of the Jobcentre Plus offices in (a) Shettleston, (b) Parkhead and (c) Easterhouse on the closure of Jobcentre Plus offices in Glasgow.","false","Biography information for Natalie McGarry","Glasgow East","Natalie McGarry","57325"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/658002","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-12-16","<p>Since 1998 the Department occupies the majority of its accommodation under a Private Finance Initiative (PFI) known as the PRIME contract. Under the terms of this 20-year PFI, the Department contracts to occupy fully serviced accommodation from its private sector partner, Telereal Trillium.</p><p> </p><p>The leases for the buildings in question are included within the provisions of this PFI arrangement and are therefore not held by DWP. Therefore we are unable to supply the information you have requested.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/658002/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-16T14:39:15.94Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/658002/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/658002/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-12-13","Jobcentres: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, who the respective landlords are of the Jobcentre Plus offices in (a) Shettleston, (b) Parkhead and (c) Easterhouse.","false","Biography information for Natalie McGarry","Glasgow East","Natalie McGarry","57326"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/658003","HM Treasury","false","2016-12-16","<p>The cost of the childcare element of working tax credits from 2010-11 onwards is available from Table 3.2 from HM Revenue and Customs' Child and Working Tax Credits statistics: finalised annual awards National Statistics publications, available at : <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/personal-tax-credits-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/personal-tax-credits-statistics</a></p><p> </p><p>These have been summarised in the table below<em>:</em></p><p>Annualised entitlement of childcare element (in £ million)</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Singles</p></td><td><p>Couples</p></td><td><p>Total</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>957</p></td><td><p>591</p></td><td><p>1,548</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>758</p></td><td><p>459</p></td><td><p>1,217</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>705</p></td><td><p>416</p></td><td><p>1,121</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>760</p></td><td><p>407</p></td><td><p>1,167</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>793</p></td><td><p>401</p></td><td><p>1,194</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/658003/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-16T11:52:13.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/658003/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/658003/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-12-13","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the cost to the public purse has been of the childcare element of working tax credits in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","57328"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/658004","HM Treasury","false","2016-12-16","<p>Tax-Free Childcare will be gradually rolled out to parents from early 2017. There is no requirement for parents to pre-register for a Tax-Free Childcare account.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/658004/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-16T14:41:20.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/658004/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/658004/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-12-13","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many families have registered a tax-free childcare account in anticipation of that scheme opening in 2017.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","57329"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/658005","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-12-16","<p>The savings were estimated using DWP's models of the tax and benefit system. Extracting the full details of the calculations carried out within the models would only be possible at disproportionate cost.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/658005/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-16T14:20:32.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/658005/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/658005/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-12-13","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 12 December 2016 to Question 56188, on children: day care, if he will publish the methodology used to calculate the estimated spend forecasts.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","57312"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/658006","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-12-16","<p>There is no backlog of Universal Credit claims. Where claims are delayed this is due to more information being required from the customer.</p><p> </p><p>Claimants in financial need can apply for an advance of Universal Credit. These requests can be made over the telephone and a decision can be made by agents on that call.</p><p> </p><p>All new Universal Credit claimants have the opportunity to discuss any concerns about how to budget their monthly payment with their work coach. Personal Budgeting Support is available online, by phone and face to face for those with budgeting difficulties.</p><p> </p><p>During December 2016, advances of Universal Credit and Personal Budgeting Support will be available as usual.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/658006/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-16T14:33:48.53Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/658006/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/658006/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-12-13","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps his Department has taken to deal with the backlog of universal credit claims; and what support there will be in December 2016 for people waiting for such claims.","false","Biography information for Drew Hendry","Inverness, Nairn, Badenoch and Strathspey","Drew Hendry","57447"
